nt of   Tilley  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Tiller","meanings":["English (southern, especially Hampshire): occupational name from Middle English <i>tiliere</i>, <i>tilyer</i> ‘one who tills the soil, husbandman, farmer, farm laborer’. This is a derivative of Old English <i>tilian</i> ‘to till (the soil)’, Middle English <i>tilie</i>. There has been some confusion of this name with   Tyler  .","German: variant of <b>Tüller</b> (see   Tuller  )."]},{"name":"Tiley","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire, Somerset and Wiltshire): variant of   Tilley  ."]}]},{"name":"Johane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Norwegian feminine form of   Johan ."],"variants":[{"name":"Joanne","meanings":["From Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, and so a doublet of   Joan .  This too was revived as a given name in its own right in the first half of the 20th century. It has to some extent been influenced by the independently formed combination <i>Jo Anne</i>."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Johane Tilley was born in 1380, in Glassenbury, Kent, England as the daughter of William Tyllye. She married Stephen Roberts in 1408, in Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1430, in Glassenbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1380–1430":"1380–1430","1350–1440":"1350–1440","1354–Male":"1354–Surnud","1408–1460":"1408–1460","1410–1499":"1410–1499","138